metadata.name: Physarum Logo #120
metadata.description:
These past few months have been a great experience and with the beta ending, I wanted to create a piece to thank all collectors and pay tribute to this great platform. 

The piece is based on a physarum simulation with a couple of tweaks, such as continuous behavioural changes and an extra information layer that further manipulates the physarum.

There are ~262k particles simulated in parallel, so it is quite GPU heavy. 

Each piece features one of 12 different colour pallets, the text and a couple of cell-like bodies running around the screen.

Controls: 
S - Save image
H - Hide Text
Click/Touch - Spawn particles

Disclaimer: This is nothing official by the platform itself, merely a tribute by an artist and fan. 

With all that said: Thank you to everyone, and see you in 1.0 !

metadata.name: Connections - v2 #7
metadata.description:
Dear collectors,
Roots was originally published as Project #1374 on November 26, 2021.
(https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/1374)
Due to a technical issue, Project #1374 has been hidden from the site and is being replaced by this reissued version.

_______________________________
Lets connect?

Connections (v1) showed in the description of its previous version an outburst of Brazilian citizens dissatisfied with their loss of monetary power due to the corruption of their government.

Now, in more mature way, this project draws luminous connections made thanks to the encounter of colored particles of a flowfield inside a Voronoi diagram, whose transparency is mapped according to the animation, bringing smoothness and fading in the transitions. As a result, we have different population divisions of these particles, like civilizations entering conurbatory processes, photographed on a dark night.

Possible Features:
> Background: Night, Blood, Deep Ocean, Wine, Swamp and Steel.
> Line colors: Reggae, Cold, Neon and Nature.
> Connection Factor: 1, 3, 7 and 11.
> Particles: 222, 333, 888, 1111 and 2222.


Go to Live View window ("open live") and press 's' to save a PNG from your canvas.

_______________________________
Creator: Kukuti
Nov2021 -> Nov2022
License: NFT 2.0

metadata.name: Totems of Unknown Creatures #7
metadata.description:
Once upon a time, some unknown creatures appeared on the vast continent to bring joy and happiness to the people, and in order to praise these creatures, people carved their appearances into stone as totems and passed them on forever.

There are two types of these totems, one is more ordinary, there is no brilliant color, and the other is covered with stars and moons, exuding a majestic brilliance, and on this kind of totems, you can even see a flickering light. 

Press 's' in live view to save the current image.

metadata.name: A Lonely Flower  #6
metadata.description:
"A Lonely Flower" is a Picture-in-picture, each of them blooms lonely but bravely.
"A Lonely Flower " is created by p5.js. Each piece is 640 x 640.
For each token, colors, shapes of each flower, length of branches, background color, bows, the size of shadow are generated, resulting in unique generative patterns for each minted item.
Press 's' in live view to save the current image.
Images may take 1 to 3 minutes to load, so please be patient.

metadata.name: Southern Gothic #55
metadata.description:
“Southern Gothic” is my debut release on the fxhash platform. The project is created entirely through code. All copyrights are released to the holder of each image output, even for commercial purposes.

“Southern Gothic” borrows its name from the literary genre made famous by writers like Flannery O’Connor and Carson McCullers. Rather than illustrating a singular setting, the code generates an entire rural townscape, thereby, blurring the boundaries between representation and narrative. The individual scenes are framed frontally with an intentionally flat aesthetic character, referencing traditional folk art of the American South. The absence of human figures within these scenes adds to their overwhelming sense of darkness and forlorn. Observing multiple scenes side-by-side, one may even get the strange feeling that something terrible has happened (or is about to happen) in this rural landscape.

Pressing the down arrow saves the coded output as a .png image.

metadata.name: Unit of me #75
metadata.description:
Just like a river, which is always flowing and changing, we are never the same from one moment to the next. Our individuality is composed of countless fragments, each with its unique size and color, that come together to form who we are at any given moment. These fragments constantly shift, some become more prominent and vibrant, while others fade into the background. We are constantly being molded and shaped by the passage of time, so that who we are today is not who we were yesterday, and will not be who we are tomorrow

13 color palettes
3 canvas proportion ratio
and more 3 different traits

Press S to save a .png

Created by Zamboni
Dec. 2022

metadata.name: Electric Hope #360
metadata.description:
Perceived as fabric of dark and vivid thoughts, hope is always there. Sparse layers of squares form an intricate colorful lattice reflecting mixed feelings of hopelessness and hopefulness, doubt and optimism.

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Inspired by CMYK halftone printing patterns

Made with p5js especially for #fxhashturnsone event. 50% of primary sales will be donated to Processing Foundation

metadata.name: Digital Gardens #251
metadata.description:
Digital Gardens are places of magic and wonder, where you can connect with your inner nature and take a deep breath. Digital Gardens are a refuge from the world outside. A sanctuary for the mind, body, and soul. But they are also a place of play and exploration. It is a space where you can let your imagination run wild, creating and discovering new things.
Digital Gardens brings to life the minimalistic essence of Detegus’ art and the abstract and rational art of Alfredo Boaron.
The gardens are generated from a recursive function dividing the space at each iteration with a proportion that follows the Fibonacci succession and randomly stops after some iterations. At each recursion the canvas is divided into two pieces following the proportion of two consecutive Fibonacci numbers [1 to 144].
The minimalistic visual effect is then personalized by the palettes of 15 artists who embraced the invitation to give their personal contribution to the collection. The palette name and the author name is displayed in the features along with the Fibonacci numbers ratio, the colors number vs the total palette color number, the background color, the total number of rectangles and the depth level of recursion achieved by the algorithm.
Immerse yourself in this generative project, inspired by geometrism and abstract expressionism. 
Lose yourself in the beauty of a digital garden.
